Regenerate CI-related YAML files

This commit was performed automatically by a script.
https://github.com/RyanGlScott/ci-maintenance

Allow building with base-4.15 on Windows

Prior to `base-4.15`, only the `System.Win32.NLS` module from `Win32` defined
a type synonym named `CodePage`, but as of `base-4.15`, `base`'s
`GHC.IO.Encoding.CodePage` module defines a duplicate version of `CodePage`.
This patch changes `System.Win32.CodePage` to avoid accidentally importing
`CodePage` a second time from `GHC.IO.Encoding.CodePage`.

Fixes #5.

Migrate from Travis CI to GitHub Actions

Travis CI recently announced
[changes to its pricing model](https://blog.travis-ci.com/2020-11-02-travis-ci-new-billing)
that will affect OSS projects. Whereas Travis previously allowed unrestricted
hours for OSS projects to run on their build machines, the new pricing model
will require the use of credits, of which free plans only have a limited
quantity. Moreover, Travis now takes an extraordinarily long time to actually
serve CI requests, which is infeasible in the long term.

As a result, I have decided
(with encouragement from other Haskell maintainers, see
[here](https://old.reddit.com/r/haskell/comments/jvbs49/psa_maintainers_should_think_about_migrating_off/))
to migrate to GitHub Actions. This
relies on a very recent version of `haskell-ci` that features a GitHub Actions
backend.

AppVeyor: Work around Windows install service bug

As suggested in
https://github.com/Mistuke/GhcChoco/issues/10#issuecomment-730441768.

Do things on non-Windows OSes, and change the locale encoding (#3)

* Attempt to adjust TextEncoding on non-Windows

If someone expects their code page to be 65001 on Windows, it seems
sensible that the TextEncoding should be utf8 on non-Windows
(especially since folks are asking for this behavior in
bos/criterion#205).

Unfortunately, this does require some breaking changes, since
`withCodePage` now can error at runtime on non-Windows if supplied
an unknown `CodePage`, and `withCodePageVerbosity` had to be renamed
to `withCodePageOptions`. Luckily, I'm not aware of anyone who
actually uses either function, so I think this breakage shouldn't be
noticeable.

Along the way, I did some much-needed refactoring, including:

* The introduction of a `System.IO.CodePage.Internal`, modules, which
  now houses the `Options` data type, among other things.
* Added support for the 1252 (Latin1) code page.

* Fix infinitely-looping thinko

* Also change the locale encoding

Changing the encoding for just stdin/stdout/stderr apparently isn't
enough for some applications. A notable example of an application
that requires the locale encoding to be changed is `bench`. See
bos/criterion#205 for more details.

* setLocaleEncoding is only offered on GHC 7.4+
